# Is global Pearson r the right metric for drug response prediction?

## The problem

Drug response prediction models are almost universally evaluated by global Pearson r —
the correlation between predicted and observed IC₅₀ across all (cell, drug) test pairs.
The implicit assumption is that a higher global r means the model has learned more about
how cancer cells respond to drugs.

This assumption deserves scrutiny.
GDSC2 IC₅₀ values span
{{ "%.1f"|format(variance_decomposition.ic50_range.min) }} to
{{ "%.1f"|format(variance_decomposition.ic50_range.max) }} LN µM across
{{ variance_decomposition.n_drugs }} drugs.
That is a large range, and most of it reflects differences between drugs — some are simply
much more potent than others, across all cell lines.
A model that ignores cell sensitivity entirely and just memorises per-drug average IC₅₀
would still produce predictions that co-vary with the truth whenever test drugs span this
range.
Global r would reward it.

Per-drug Pearson r is an alternative that removes this confound.
It computes correlation within each drug over its test cell lines, then averages across drugs.
A model that only memorises per-drug means has zero per-drug r by construction —
its predictions are constant within each drug, and a constant has no correlation with anything.

The question is whether these two metrics are measuring genuinely different things,
and if so, which one reflects the clinically relevant ability: ranking cell lines by
their sensitivity to a specific drug.

## Experimental strategy

Rather than making one argument, the experiment assembles four independent lines of
evidence, each designed to block a different counterargument.

The first asks whether the suspected confound is large enough to matter, using only data
and no model at all.
The second tests whether the metrics can be experimentally dissociated — whether a
predictor can be constructed that scores high on one and zero on the other.
The third checks whether the gap between metrics is a consequence of model underfitting
that would close with more capacity.
The fourth asks whether the gap is specific to a particular evaluation protocol or
whether it generalises.

## Step 1 — How much of IC₅₀ variance is between drugs?

The variance of IC₅₀ across all
{{ "{:,}".format(variance_decomposition.n_pairs) }}
(cell, drug) pairs can be decomposed into a between-drug component and a within-drug
component by the law of total variance.
If between-drug variance dominates, then knowing the per-drug mean is already most of
the signal, and global r will largely reward that knowledge.

The decomposition gives between-drug variance =
{{ "%.4f"|format(variance_decomposition.between_drug_var) }}
out of a total of
{{ "%.4f"|format(variance_decomposition.total_var) }},
a fraction of
**{{ "%.1f"|format(variance_decomposition.between_drug_var_fraction * 100) }}%**.
From this, the theoretical ceiling on global r for a model that knows only per-drug
means — and nothing about individual cell lines — is
`sqrt({{ "%.4f"|format(variance_decomposition.between_drug_var) }} / {{ "%.4f"|format(variance_decomposition.total_var) }}) = {{ "%.3f"|format(variance_decomposition.global_r_ceiling_from_between) }}`.

Nearly 70% of all IC₅₀ variance comes from differences between drugs rather than
differences between cell lines within a drug.
A model with no cell-sensitivity ability can in principle reach global r near 0.83.
This tells us the concern is not hypothetical — the scale of the between-drug confound
is large enough to dominate global r in practice.

## Step 2 — Can the two metrics be dissociated experimentally?

The variance decomposition establishes a structural argument.
Step 2 tests it empirically by constructing two extreme predictors designed to have
opposite metric profiles.

**Predictor 2A** produces the per-drug mean IC₅₀ as its prediction for every
(cell, drug) pair — it has perfect knowledge of between-drug differences and zero
knowledge of cell sensitivity.
Evaluated under the drug_blind split, it achieves global r =
{{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.predictor_2a.mean_global_r) }} ± {{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.predictor_2a.std_global_r) }},
exactly matching the Step 1 ceiling of
{{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.step1_vs_2a_validation.theoretical_ceiling) }}
within {{ "%.4f"|format(baseline_dissociation.step1_vs_2a_validation.abs_diff) }}.
Its per-drug r is 0.0 by construction — it cannot rank cell lines because its predictions
are constant within each drug.

**Predictor 2B** starts from OmniCancerV1's drug_blind predictions and removes the
between-drug component by subtracting the per-drug mean of the test predictions:
`ŷ_resid(c, d) = ŷ(c, d) − mean_{c'} ŷ(c', d)`.
This operation leaves the within-drug ranking of cell lines intact but strips out all
between-drug signal.
The result: global r falls from
{{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.predictor_2b.mean_original_global_r) }} to
{{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.predictor_2b.mean_resid_global_r) }},
while per-drug r is exactly preserved at
{{ "%.3f"|format(baseline_dissociation.predictor_2b.mean_resid_per_drug_r) }}.

Together, 2A and 2B demonstrate that the two metrics are orthogonal.
One responds only to between-drug signal; the other responds only to within-drug signal.
They are not two estimates of the same quantity.

## Step 3 — Is the gap an artefact of underfitting?

If the gap between global r and per-drug r merely reflects a model that has not been
trained well enough, then larger models should close it.
This is a plausible concern: a perfectly fitted model would learn both between-drug and
within-drug structure, and the two metrics should converge.

Five models of increasing capacity are trained under the same drug_blind protocol:
Ridge regression, three MLP sizes (S, M, L), and OmniCancerV1 (attention-based).

