| {{ name }} | {{ "%.3f"|format(m.mean_global_r) }} ± {{ "%.3f"|format(m.std_global_r) }} | {{ "%.3f"|format(m.mean_per_drug_r) }} ± {{ "%.3f"|format(m.std_per_drug_r) }} | **+{{ "%.3f"|format(m.mean_gap) }}** | [{{ "%.3f"|format(m.gap_95ci[0]) }}, {{ "%.3f"|format(m.gap_95ci[1]) }}] | {{ "%.4f"|format(m.gap_ttest_p) }} |
{% endfor %}
The gap is positive and statistically significant across all five models.
The gap narrows across MLP sizes (from +{{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models['MLP-S'].mean_gap) }} at MLP-S to +{{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models['MLP-L'].mean_gap) }} at MLP-L)
but does not converge to zero — the MLP-L 95% CI of
[{{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models['MLP-L'].gap_95ci[0]) }}, {{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models['MLP-L'].gap_95ci[1]) }}]
excludes zero.
Critically, OmniCancerV1 — a qualitatively different architecture with drug-feature inputs —
reverses the MLP trend and widens the gap to +{{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models.OmniCancerV1.mean_gap) }},
showing that the narrowing within the MLP family is an architecture-specific artefact
rather than evidence of convergence.
The gap is not a model limitation — it is a property of what the metric measures.

## Step 4 — Does the gap generalise across evaluation protocols?

Drug_blind is one of three standard splits in this codebase.
It is also the evaluation scenario closest to real deployment: test drugs were never
seen during training, so the model must generalise to genuinely novel compounds.
This is precisely the scenario where a reliable evaluation metric is most needed.
Under mixed_set and cell_blind, by contrast, test drugs appear in the training set,
which gives the model an opportunity to memorise per-drug means during training.
If global r inflation is indeed driven by drug-mean memorisation, it should be amplified
under those splits and reduced under drug_blind.

OmniCancerV1 is evaluated under all three splits:

| Split | Global r | Per-drug r | Gap | 95% CI | p |
|-------|----------|------------|-----|--------|---|
{% for split, s in cross_split.splits.items() -%}
| {{ split }} | {{ "%.3f"|format(s.mean_global_r) }} | {{ "%.3f"|format(s.mean_per_drug_r) }} | {{ "%+.3f"|format(s.mean_gap) }} | [{{ "%.3f"|format(s.gap_95ci[0]) }}, {{ "%.3f"|format(s.gap_95ci[1]) }}] | {{ "%.4f"|format(s.gap_ttest_p) }} |
{% endfor %}
The pattern is striking.
Under drug_blind, global r is low ({{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.drug_blind.mean_global_r) }})
and per-drug r is high ({{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.drug_blind.mean_per_drug_r) }}).
Under mixed_set and cell_blind, where the model has seen the test drugs during training,
global r jumps to
{{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.mixed_set.mean_global_r) }} and
{{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.cell_blind.mean_global_r) }} respectively —
values that superficially look like strong model performance.
Per-drug r under these same conditions is
{{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.mixed_set.mean_per_drug_r) }} and
{{ "%.3f"|format(cross_split.splits.cell_blind.mean_per_drug_r) }},
neither of which matches the global r narrative.

The split-dependence of global r is itself the most direct evidence of the memorisation
mechanism: the metric is sensitive to whether test drugs were in the training set, while
per-drug r is not.
A good metric should measure the model's ability to generalise, not whether it has
seen the test labels before.

## Interpretation

The four steps converge on one conclusion.
Between-drug variance dominates GDSC2 IC₅₀ ({{ "%.1f"|format(variance_decomposition.between_drug_var_fraction * 100) }}%),
creating a structural ceiling that any drug-mean memoriser can approach.
The empirical ceiling matches the theory to within {{ "%.4f"|format(baseline_dissociation.step1_vs_2a_validation.abs_diff) }}.
Removing between-drug signal from predictions collapses global r while leaving per-drug r
unchanged, confirming the metrics are orthogonal.
Scaling model capacity by orders of magnitude does not close the gap, ruling out
underfitting.
The gap's sign reverses across splits in exactly the way the memorisation mechanism
predicts.

Global r is not a reliable measure of cell-sensitivity prediction ability.
Which metric should replace it is a question for a separate experiment; what this
experiment establishes is that global r cannot be trusted as a primary metric for
drug response prediction models.
For subsequent experiments in this series, global r is reported as secondary context
only.
The OmniCancerV1 drug_blind baseline that anchors those experiments is
per-drug r = {{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models.OmniCancerV1.mean_per_drug_r) }} ± {{ "%.3f"|format(model_comparison.models.OmniCancerV1.std_per_drug_r) }},
not global r ≈ {{ "%.2f"|format(model_comparison.models.OmniCancerV1.mean_global_r) }}.

## Prior work on evaluation metrics

Two evaluation protocols coexist in the drug response prediction literature, and the
choice between them has been determined by model architecture rather than deliberate
metric selection.

Papers that train a single model across all drugs and cell lines — PASO
([Wu et al., PLoS Comput Biol 2025](https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pcbi.1012905)),
DeepCDR
([Liu et al., Bioinformatics 2020](https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btaa822)),
TGSA
([Zhu et al., Bioinformatics 2022](https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btab290)) —
report global Pearson r as the primary metric.
Papers that train a separate model for each drug — Carli et al.
([Nat Commun 2025](https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-025-56827-5)),
DeepCCDS
([Wu et al., Adv Sci 2025](https://doi.org/10.1002/advs.202416958)) —
report per-drug r not by deliberate choice but because the one-model-per-drug
architecture forces it.

Bernett et al.
([bioRxiv 2025](https://doi.org/10.1101/2025.05.26.655288))
introduce DrEval, a benchmarking framework that identifies biased evaluation metrics
as one of six systemic problems in the field, and report that deep learning models
barely outperform a naive mean-effects predictor — convergent evidence for the
drug-mean inflation described here.
DrEval addresses the problem through standardised split protocols and cross-study
benchmarks rather than metric decomposition.

Sealfon et al.
([J. Cheminformatics 17:28, 2025](https://doi.org/10.1186/s13321-025-00965-x))
independently identify the same problem under the framing of a "specification game":
their DummyDrugAvg predictor achieves global r ≈ 0.85 with per-drug r = 0.00,
and they endorse per-drug r as the appropriate metric for joint models.
That paper establishes the problem descriptively on a single dataset; it does not
provide a formal variance decomposition, test whether the gap persists across model
capacities, or examine the split-dependence of global r inflation.
This experiment provides those four lines of evidence and the experimental
justification for adopting per-drug r as the primary metric.

## Limitations

Step 3 trains all models under the drug_blind split only; whether the capacity effect
holds under other splits is not tested here.
OmniCancerV1 training is capped at 50 epochs, while Ridge and MLP models use
early stopping, so cross-model capacity comparisons are approximate.
Per-drug r excludes drugs with fewer than 5 test cell lines; under drug_blind
Step 3 evaluates 22–24 drugs per fold.
The variance decomposition is computed over the full paired dataset; fold-level
variance may differ slightly.
Predictor 2B subtracts per-drug means computed from the test split itself — an oracle
condition, since those means would not be available at deployment time.
This means 2B's per-drug r preservation is a best-case demonstration of metric
orthogonality, not a deployable predictor; the dissociation argument holds regardless.
